<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOR MY BROTHER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jane Reavill Ransom, From Without Asking (Story Line Press, 403 Continental 
St., Santa Cruz, CA 95060: $9.95, paper; 0-934257-29-9). Ransom, granddaughter 
of the poet and critic John Crowe Ransom, spent a year as a girl with her 
family in Almunecar, on Spain's Mediterranean coast and later years as an 
exchange student and teacher. Since 1984 she has been an international editor 
at the New York Daily News. Without Asking is the 1989 winner of the Nicholas 
Roerich Poetry Prize. 1989, Jane Reivill Ransom. Reprinted by permission of 
Story Line Press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
We knelt in the recess of a hollowed rock. 
</P>
<P>
We lit a driftwood pyre with your magnifying glass. 
</P>
<P>
The roasting pinecone opened itself 
</P>
<P>
like a mother's hand. We ate the flesh 
</P>
<P>
of its seeds. Nearby 
</P>
<P>
the Mediterranean ticked without stop 
</P>
<P>
above the angelfish 
</P>
<P>
while behind our cave, in the cliff-side house, 
</P>
<P>
she placed a note in Father's typewriter: 
</P>
<P>
I give up, 
</P>
<P>
since you want me still 
</P>
<P>
and silent. 
</P>
<P>
I believe the ink unfurled, frail as a spider, 
</P>
<P>
when he smoothed out the sheet. 
</P>
<P>
Then he crushed it 
</P>
<P>
in his palm. Yes, I know, you and I had filled 
</P>
<P>
our ears, like conch shells, 
</P>
<P>
with noise. But no matter: 
</P>
<P>
What happened next 
</P>
<P>
we could not have stopped. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Jane Reavill Ransom 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
