<HEADLINE>
<P>
ANTI-SAVINGS POLICIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Concerning James Flanigan's column in August, as a baby boomer, I'm not going 
to rely on Social Security just because the government says it's "safe." That's 
like letting a drunk drive you home, just because he promises he will deliver 
you home "safely." 
</P>
<P>
Once you realize that the so-called cash reserves are really just paper, you 
won't feel so secure. Here's how the government "invests" the Social Security 
surplus. They just give this extra money to other government agencies that need 
it. That agency then issues Social Security a bond (really an IOU). 
</P>
<P>
Thus, the buildup of the Social Security "cash" reserves is really just a 
buildup of the national debt. The money isn't in a bank account, waiting to be 
withdrawn. When the baby boomers retire, the national debt must be converted to 
cash to pay benefits. How will this happen? Either the government must develop 
a surplus in other areas,or it must put a tremendous tax burden on our 
children. Both of these aren't very likely. Most likely, Social Security will 
cut our benefits. 
</P>
<P>
I'm relying on my own savings for retirement. 
</P>
<P>
STEVEN G. VERNON 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
