<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOME PROTECTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It was fine that Stephen J. Frazier of San Diego wrote to correct an error on 
the river that flows through his home state of Vermont (Letters, Sept. 10), but 
why did he have to add the last sentence: "I only hope you didn't encourage too 
many of them to visit"? 
</P>
<P>
If he is so protective of his home state, why isn't he back there protecting it 
instead of being in San Diego taking advantage of its opportunities? Did 
California discourage him from visiting or moving in? Isn't there enough room 
in the United States for each of us to find our own chosen visiting or living 
space? 
</P>
<P>
VICKIE L. SPRATT 
</P>
<P>
Pomona 
</P>
</TEXT>
