<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALLA BREVE:: EILEEN FARRELL SINGS HAROLD ARLEN. REFERENCE RECORDINGS, RR30CD 
(COMPACT DISC). 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Walter Price 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Recorded a year ago when she was 69, this disc of superb Arlen songs represents 
a comeback of sorts for soprano Farrell, who always had an interest in pop 
music. She was more successful than most classical singers in attempting to 
cross the line, yet her work has a slickness and sameness that is ultimately 
unconvincing. Here, she is at her best in the bouncy material such as "Let's 
Fall in Love," hopelessly out of her element in "A Woman's Prerogative," not to 
mention a passionless "Happiness Is Just a Thing Called Joe." In addition, 
there is a lot of flat singing, which may or may not be an intentional 
mannerism. Loonis McGlohon's arrangements suit the occasion. Walter Price 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Soprano Eileen Farrell: A comeback of sorts 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
