</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA092489-0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 111601 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
September 24, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Page 61; Calendar Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
79 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALLA BREVE:: SONGS OF RODGERS &amp; HAMMERSTEIN; SAMUEL RAMEY, BASS; NATIONAL 
PHILHARMONIC, PETER MATZ CONDUCTING. EMI 7 49581 2 (COMPACT DISC). 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Walter Price 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ramey admirably lightens his sound for such numbers as "June is bustin' out 
allover!" and "The surrey with the fringe on top." "A fellow needs a girl" and 
"Some enchanted evening" are genuinely touching. But in such muscular, treacly 
numbers as "Climb ev'ry mountain" and "You'll never walk alone" he sounds for 
all the world like one of Verdi's fathers or priests singing in an English 
translation. Still, for show-tune aficionados the disc is worth having. Walter 
Price 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Basist Samuel Ramey: Songs from Rodgers &amp; Hammerstein 
