<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Recording Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA092489-0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 111602 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
September 24, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Page 61; Calendar Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
102 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALLA BREVE:: SAINT-SAENS: "SAMSON ET DALILA." CHRISTA LUDWIG, JAMES KING, BERND 
WEIKL; CHORUS OF THE BAVARIAN RADIO AND MUNICH RADIO ORCHESTRA CONDUCTED BY 
GIUSEPPE PATANE. EURODISC 7793-2-RG (TWO COMPACT DISCS). 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Allan Ulrich 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In Patane's lackluster approach, Saint-Saens' most familiar opera still sounds 
like an oratorio with moving parts. Neither sufficiently suave nor enjoyably 
vulgar, the conductor offers little assistance to a mismatched, unidiomatic 
international cast. Even in 1973, when the recording was made, Ludwig sounded 
hollow at the bottom, and a voice never noted for pure sensuality makes rough 
going of Delilah's lush musical line. King's reliable, stolid Samson misses Old 
Testament fervor and even a dram of poetry. Originally issued on RCA, the 
compact disc remastering is excessively reverberant. Allan Ulrich 
</P>
</TEXT>
