<P>
QUAYLE BACKS JAPAN TIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Vice President Dan Quayle, who toured two northern Japan military bases on the 
third day of his Far East visit, said that the U.S.-Japan Security Treaty must 
not be touched. "Anybody who thinks you ought to tamper, rewrite or modify the 
U.S.-Japan Security Treaty is wrong," Quayle told reporters during a flight to 
Chitose and Misawa, the two main air bases guarding northern Japan. Japan's 
opposition Socialist Party has called for scaling back U.S.-Japan military 
ties. In the Philippines, the May One Movement, a 750,000-member labor group, 
accused the United States of attempting to pressure Manila to extend the lease 
on key U.S. military bases and vowed protests during Quayle's visit, which 
begins Tuesday. 
</P>
